ANC Chief Whip Jackson Mthembu is demanding R1 million from SABC group executive of corporate affairs Hlaudi Motsoeneng for defamation. JOHANNESBURG - The African National Congress (ANC) says its chief whip Jackson Mthembu has lodged a legal claim against South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC) group executive of corporate affairs Hlaudi Motsoeneng, after Motsoeneng warned Mthembu on live television to stop talking about the SABC. Motsoeneng had claimed that if Mthembu did not stop criticising him, he would reveal details about a business transaction he claimed Mthembu wanted help with.Mthembu suing HlaudiMotsoeneng for &#39;malicious &amp; defamatory&#39; claims &amp; threats during a New Age business briefing aired live a few weeks agoGD#Hlaudi Motsoneng claimed on live TV that if Mthembu did not shut up, he would reveal details about Mthembu&#39;s conduct. SGMthembu has strongly criticised Motsoeneng, saying he has embarrassed the government and the ANC.The ANC says Mthembu s lawyers have sent a letter of demand to Motsoeneng, insisting that he immediately apologise for making the comments and retract them.Mthembu is also asking Motsoeneng to pay him a sum of R1 million.He says he is not intimidated by Motsoeneng s threats and hopes that a court ruling against him will stop him from making similar thoughtless utterances in future. (Edited by Zamangwane Shange)